explain:

explain:
During this game, you can move a variety of items. You can throw balls into the hexagonal bin. You can put credit cards, CDs, and pencils into the bin. You can also place the credit cards, CDs, and pencils into the top drawer.

You will EARN one point for each of the credit cards and CDs in the hexagonal bin. But you will LOSE three points for each ball inside the bin, each credit card and CD not collected, and each credit card, CD, and pencil in the top drawer. You will neither gain nor lose points for pencils in the bin or not collected.
overall: If the player knows the exact scoring rules in advance, the scoring rules are pointless. If the player doesn't know the exact scoring rules in advance, they should be told that some of the tasks will earn points and some will lose points, or they will feel cheated.

overall: That sounds like a fun and active game! It seems like it requires both accuracy and quick reflexes to avoid landing dodgeballs in the doggie beds. The scoring system adds an interesting twist, encouraging players to aim carefully while also keeping an eye on where the dodgeballs end up. Overall, it sounds like a great way to get some exercise and have some laughs!

explain: this game seems like a thrilling mix of precision and strategy
overall: This game seems like a clever blend of physical activity, coordination, and strategy. The objective of throwing dodgeballs around the room while aiming to have them stop moving without landing in the doggie beds adds an exciting challenge. The scoring system, with points awarded for successfully stopped dodgeballs and penalties for those landing in the beds, adds a layer of competition and risk management. Overall, it appears to be an engaging and entertaining game suitable for groups looking for active fun.

explain: in this game player need to throw the dodgeball at various tragets within a room
overall: This game seems like a dynamic and entertaining activity that combines elements of accuracy, strategy, and coordination. The inclusion of various targets, such as the hexagonal bin, bed, and desk, adds diversity to the gameplay and requires players to adapt their throwing technique accordingly. The scoring system, which rewards successful throws with points, motivates players to aim for precision while adding a competitive edge to the game. explain: Throw dodgeballs so that they land on the doggie bed or bin or stop moving. 1 point for each ball on the dog bed, 1 point for each ball on a bin, and 1 point for each ball that stops after being thrown.
overall: I think this game makes sense for the most part. The scoring part doesn't make much sense since I would assume all the balls stop moving after being thrown. This would mean you just throw the ball anywhere and you will get a point.

explain: Throw balls and place credit cards or CDs into a bin. For each ball that goes into the bin, multiply this by the number of credit cards or CDs in the bin and add 1 point for each ball thrown.
overall: This game is somewhat simple and the instructions make sense. The scoring is not that good and does not make too much sense in terms of being fun and interactive. Sounds kind of boring.

explain: Place a bin near the rug. Throw dodgeballs into it, on the bed, on the desk, or on top of the bin. For each throw that gets the ball to stop in these spots, get 1 point. Add all points up for the score.
overall: I like this game. The scoring is simple and easy to understand. The gameplay is also simple and makes sense.

explain: Place a bin near the center of the room. Move objects into the bin by picking them up or setting them in motion. For each different object that is moved into the bin by the end of the game you score 1 point.
overall: I think the game sounds okay and like a game. The gameplay and scoring makes sense for the most part. I would like this game but would not play it for long.

explain: Place all balls on the desk, put the bin on the bed, and keep them there. Stand next to the desk and throw balls into the bin. After throwing  the balls 5 times, the game ends. Your score at the end is determined by each ball that stops moving inside the bin.
overall: I think this game does not make much sense and has a lot of steps that do not add up. The scoring is definitely the weirdest part and should be different. I would not like this game.

explain: This game is like trick-shotting. The ol' classic of utilizing hand-eye coordination to judge a distance and try to land the object being thrown at or on a certain target.
overall: I used to do this a lot in my youth. It was a lot of fun then, less so now, but still is somewhat. For younger people and those who enjoy trick shots, I'd say this would be pretty fun. It's a basic game, but an enduring classic for a reason.

explain: This game requires a ball, a ramp-like object, and a mat or rug with different color patches on it. The objective of the game is to throw the ball so that it rolls on the ramp and stops at a certain point on the rug. Different colored squares represent different point values in either gains or losses.
overall: This game would be difficult for me personally, trying to get the amount of momentum correct for the ball to stop on the colored square with the highest point value. It's again a basic game that wouldn't hold my attention for long now at my current age, but for younger people, I imagine they would be excited learning to control their throws to try to score points. It reminds me a little of bowling and trains similar skills.

explain: In this game, place a hexagonal bin near the rug in the open space of the room and grab a dodgeball. Throw the dodgeball and try to land it inside the bin. Each successful land of the ball inside the bin equals 1 point earned. Retrieve the ball and try again.
overall: This game is very easy and can be done with most any container and throwable object that won't break. I would get bored of this game pretty quick as I believe I could nail most every throw.

explain: In this game, throw a dodgeball so that it lands either inside a doggie bed, a hexagonal bin, or simply wait until it stops moving after being thrown. Gain 1 point for any of the actions described above.
overall: This game's scope is too broad. The player can score points for doing basically everything and there is no clear objective to focus on. It is basically just "throw the ball and wherever it lands, you score points." That is super boring.

explain: Setup a cured wooden ramp next to a hexagonal bin, making sure that the two objects stay together for the entire game. Grab a dodgeball and throw it so that it touches the ramp and then lands inside the bin. You earn 1 point every time the dodgeball touches the ramp and then lands inside the bin.
overall: This game, I think, would be pretty fun. Depending on how far away from the setup I am when throwing, I would have to calculate force, speed, and angles, bringing in some geometry. Something like this would keep me entertained for an afternoon and would be great for a party game.

explain: Set up a hexagonal bin and grab a red dodgeball. Throw the ball into the bin without it touching the floor. The game ends after throwing the dodgeball 10 times or as soon as it has successfully made it into the bin. You score 5 points if the ball makes it into the bin at least once, 2 points if you can get it into the bin within 5 tries, and 3 more points if you can get the ball into the bin on the first try.
overall: This game is a mess and all over the place. The instructions contradict each other and are confusing. The gameplay and win conditions don't line up properly.

explain: Place a hexagonal bin near the door. After that, move objects around the room to specific locations: the top shelf, near the floor, and at the north wall. Once that is done, the objective is to throw dodgeballs so that they land still on top of the hexagonal bin. Your final score is the sum of all the points from moving the objects to different locations around the room and for each dodgeball that lands on the hexagonal bin.
overall: The instructions for this game would be annoying to carry out as it is like rearranging the entire room for no good reason. The other objects in the room as well have no clear relation with the bin and the ball, and this game is unnecessarily complicated and not fun. It is creative though, I will say that.

explain: Put a hexagonal bin near the rug and ensure it stays in its spot throughout the game. Place the chairs in the room on the desk and then throw basketballs so they land on top of the bin. For every chair on a desk, earn 1 point. For every basketball that stops moving on top of the bin, earn 40 points.
overall: Placing chairs on desks is such a random element to a game that it is almost comical. I definitely wouldn't recommend a game like this is real life and even in this virtual space, I'm immediately taken out of the immersive experience to laugh at the absurdity.

explain: Grab the hexagonal bin and put it near the rug, making sure it stays there for the duration of the game. Hold a dodgeball and throw it so that it banks off the top shelf and then lands and rests on the hexagonal bin. You earn 1 point for every dodgeball that successfully touches the shelf and then stops on top of the bin.
overall: Once again, this game involves geometry and angles and I like it. Very good for training spatial awareness and reasoning. As long as nothing is getting knocked off the shelf by the force of the ball, this would be a fun game to move the bin around between sets and practice throwing the ball at different angles.

explain: In this game, throw both golf balls and dodgeballs, aiming to land them on top of a hexagonal bin. You score 1 point for every dodgeball that stops inside the bin and 1 point for every ball of either type that lands and stops on top of the bin.
overall: The game itself is pretty standard, but the points system is a little off. There should be different point values, rather than every action all yielding the same amount of 1 point.

overall: It seems like a fun target game, albeit a little easy. wish there was tiered scoring

explain: We must throw objects into a bin. Each object has a different value which is determined by the number of dodgeballs that you've also thrown within that round.
overall: I think that the game has somewhat of a base in terms of what to use, but it's not really fully developed in terms of the objective of the game once it begins. I'm not really certain if my aim is to have the objects land inside the bin or to just hit the top of the bin.

explain: Try to get as many dodgeballs onto the shelf as possible by throwing them and have them land and stay.
overall: This seems like a very easy game to grasp, but a very difficult one to master. It reminds me of those bottle flipping games that's captured a lot of younger crowds on social media. I think it's decent, but the difficulty would probably detract a lot of gamers over time.

explain: Try to throw the dodgeballs into or onto the bin, or on the dog bed.
overall: I think it's a fun game, but without a timer it can lead to people stopping before any particular score is tallied. I think the ease of this game might attract a very young demographic, but for anyone older I think the lack of difficulty would bore others.

explain: Try to get a specific object into a specific destination. Balls must land inside the bin, cube blocks should land on the top shelf, and pillows should be in the dog bed either by toss or direct placement.
overall: I think that game described sounded a bit enticing with the challenge (but not impossible) objective of throwing the ball and the cube into their respective locations. However, the game became too easy when we were given the option to just simply place the pillow into the dog bed. I think to maintain a level of challenge, all objects should remain in a throw state and not allowed to be placed as that should be defined as cheating.

explain: Stack blocks into directed bridge designs to earn points that is based around the color of the stacked block. To earn the most points, you're objective is to aim for flat gray blocks to stack. Otherwise, you can play it safe and throw a dodgeball that will earn you 1 point every time they stop bouncing around.
overall: Perhaps it's my lack of visual understanding of the game, but I'm not really sure that there's any sort of endpoint here. While I like the idea of differentiating point values based around our design abilities, I'm not really sure what consequences or gains of the dodgeball being used since I can get 1 point with the bridge design objective.

explain: After placing the bin by the rug and shelf, your objective will be to throw the dodgeball ensuring that it touches the shelf before landing on top of the bin. You get 1 point for every successful toss that leads to this action.
overall: I think this game would be easy to explain to someone and even easier to grasp. However, I think this game would lead to a lot of frustrations for the players as they develop the skill to pull of the action. This game seems like it can foster a lot of competition which would drive that frustration, but not the game's design itself which I think makes for a great game.

explain: After we place the bin near the rug, it must not move. Our two items are tan blocks and dodgeballs. For each block that lands into the bin we get 1 point, and for each dodgeball that lands on top of the bin we also get 1 point. Your overall score is these two-point totals combined.
overall: I think this game is clear-cut in its understanding and overall objective. This might be something that some of us experienced as a carnival game or in other video games. I like the idea of having 2 ways to score points that both require different levels of skill. It feels fair and approachable overall.

explain: Place the wood ramp next to the rug for setting up the game space. The objective of the game is to grab a beachball and throw it so that lands onto the ramp and rolls onto the rug. Your score is determined by the ball's location on the rug which is broken down as zones of the rug. The zone's points range from 1 to 4 point, including one where can you also lose 1 point if it lands on one of those six zones.
overall: I love games like this as they provide a lot of variety with a pretty minimal layer of randomness. Small things can add up in each throw which I think will have people pulled in and immersed as they play trying to be their last high score! My favorite one so far.

explain: Stand near the desk with a dodgeball. Your objective is to throw the dodgeball, so it hits the south wall and stops afterward. You'll have 60 seconds to hit the south wall where you'll earn 1 point for each stopped dodgeball that accomplishes this.
overall: Overall, I believe I somewhat understand the objective of the game, but it doesn't really sound that difficult or entertaining. I'm not really sure how I could be holding the ball I threw or why I would hold a teddy bear within this game, so it'll be easy to gain points and not really lose any which makes the game feel less challenging.

explain: Your objective will be to hit the wall with a ball and to then follow up with some sort of contact with that ball before it lands. To earn points, you MUST either catch it or touch AFTER it touches a wall. You'll earn 1 point if you accomplish this successfully.
overall: I like the idea of having to move around so the notion of throwing the ball then having to rush to make contact with it after it hits a wall can be the side effect of a little workout. Also, it sounds like a pretty fun mindless game not very competitive but can instead incorporate teamwork as a cooperative mode. It doesn't sound hard, but it still can be a good time.

explain: To set up for playing this game, a hexagonal bin must be placed and remain near the rug for the duration of the game. explain: To play this game, set up by placing all golf balls, dodgeballs, triangle blocks, and pyramid blocks near a side table making sure no chair is directly in front of the desk for the duration of the game. A curved wooden ramp should be placed so that the front is adjacent to the front of the desk and a hexagonal bin should be placed facing the back of the ramp. All objects placed should remain where they are the whole game. Start the game by standing next to the bed and throwing golf balls, dodgeballs, triangle blocks, and pyramid blocks at the hexagonal bin, or so they touch a desktop or laptop computer. Golf balls have an additional condition of having to touch the ramp before landing in the hexagonal bin. Point values are as follows: Triangle Block - 1pt, Pyramid Block - 2pts, Dodgeball - 2pts, Golf Ball - 3pts. Points come from landing in the hexagonal bin. An additional 6 pts may be earned by touching the golf ball to the ramp before landing in the bin. For each object that touches a computer, a point is lost.
overall: The game is a bit convoluted but appears to be pretty interesting. The game play is a bit difficult to understand but the scoring system makes it make more sense. The game has enough layers to be engaging without being too difficult to achieve.

explain: To play this game, place a hexagonal bin near the door where it will remain during gameplay. Throw golf balls and dodgeballs at the bin, trying to land on top of or inside the bin. overall: This game is a fairly simple concept but the scoring system makes it interesting. I like that the different balls have different objectives. It looks like it would be fairly difficult to master which makes it challenging and fun.

overall: Since they're cube blocks, the odds of them moving after placing it down is low so immediately the best way to score points is to just pick it up, set it down, and pick it up again. Though the repetitiveness will set in very quickly.

explain: Setup of placing green gold ball near door making sure it stays there for entire game and placing at least one dodgeball near said green golf ball during game. You get 10 points for each different object you throw into hex bin while standing next to green golf ball. Goal is to get as many points as possible before game ends when you have thrown same dodgeball and it's stopped moving more than once or when you have thrown and stopped at least 3 different objects.
overall: Objective is to make sure the objects you throw stop in hex bin is stopped. You should use dodgeball once then other objects since it said you should place at least one dodgeball near green golf ball and the game ends when you have thrown same dodgeball or thrown and stopped at least 3 different objects.

explain: You score a point each by letting of chair and it stops moving and you get 4 points for each chair on desk that is still moving without you at end of the game. Game ends when you score 10 or more.
overall: I don't get the point. If the game ends when score is 10 or more, then is the goal to see how far you can get past 10 in one go or more likely, how fast you accomplish ending the game. Kinda like a speedrun to get to 10 points except the gameplay is just letting go of chair and in such a way as to have them keep moving, which isn't specified as to how long they expect it to be moving and what definition of moving counts. Just confusing honestly.

explain: Setup put hex bin near rug. You get 1 point for every dodgeball you throw that stops on desk and or 70 points for every one that stops on hex bin after rolling on rug.
overall: Simple but potentially fun game. Although because of the way the scoring works and there's no time limit, I guess it's just play until you get tired? Either way, why waste time and effort throwing when you can roll the ball on rug to the bin to get 70 points. Even if you fail tons of times, just getting it once is equivalent to throwing 70 successful balls on desk, which seems to be a chore honestly.

explain: You throw different types of balls onto a doggie bed that needs to be placed near center of room at start. You get different points based on what ball you use and whether it touches walls and then land in middle or ones that only land on middle without touching any walls. The points for landing on doggie bed without touching walls are 1 for basketball, 2 for beachball, and 3 for dodgeball. Otherwise for those that touch wall and then get onto middle, it's 2 for basketball, 3 for beachball, and 4 for dodgeball.
overall: So it's like getting any of the 3 balls (basket, beach, and dodge) into nothing but net or rebounding off wall before landing in, except it's on a doggie bed instead. Simple but seems fun and easy enough to understand and potentially fun to do since there's a variety of ball sizes and points for them.

explain: Put hex bin near rug and throw dodgeballs to a rest either on doggie bed or hex bin. Your score is the sum of the successful throws.
overall: Simple throwing game with dodgeball except there's two types of goals being the doggie bed or hex bin. Since there's no difference between points stated, it's just choose one you do well in and sticking with it for an indeterminable amount of time or until you get bored, which will likely be quickly.

explain: Place chair, hex bin, teddy bear, and triangular ramp in room During game, move teddy bear to chair and keep ramp near center of room with chair in front of it positioned between ramp and hex bin. Then place balls near hex bin. Gameplay is to pick up and throw teddy bear so it lands inside hex bin or it touches a ball, 5 points for landing in bin and 1 for touching a ball.
overall: A lot of setup that doesn't seem to matter. So if you're placing balls near hex bin and the points are earned by throwing teddy bear into hex bin or onto balls near it, then what's the point of the ramp or chair? To obfuscate stuff? It just seems unnecessary and busy for no reason.

explain: In this game you are trying to get a ball into a hexagonal bin without the ball touching the floor. You can get extra points for getting the ball in fewer attempts.
overall: It seems pretty boring and simple

explain: The goal is to get balls into either the hexagonal bin or a doggie bed. You get 1 point for the ball landing in either place or if the ball stops moving after you throw it.
overall: This game seems pretty boring and like it is way too easy to score points

explain: In the game you are trying to throw golfballs into a hexagonal bin. You are also trying to stack blocks on top of each other.
overall: This game is very confusing. I am not sure how the golf balls interact with the blocks or why the scoring so heavily depends on the blocks.

explain: You just put balls onto the bed
overall: This is not really a game at all, it is just moving objects to a new place

explain: You pick up a block and either throw it onto the rug or put it down and pick it back up. You get more points for picking it up and putting it back down.
overall: This game makes it way too easy to get points

explain: The goal of the game is to throw a dodgeball into a hexagonal bin
overall: This is basically diy basketball

explain: You roll a beachball down a ramp and get a varied amount of points based on where it lands
overall: This game seems fun and like there would definitely be a learning curve

explain: You move a bunch of objects and then roll golf balls on the rug
overall: This game doesn't seem fun at all, you are just moving objects and rolling golf balls on an easy target

explain: The goal is to throw a ball into or on top of a hexagonal bin and to move blocks
overall: The rolling the ball and stacking the blocks seem completely unrelated

explain: You are trying to throw a ball so that you get it to hit the top of the shelf and then ultimately land on the hexagonal bin
overall: This is similar to basketball but with the added need for hitting the shelf (backboard)

explain: The user should play with a goal to relocate all credit-cards (CC) and compact disks (CD) into the hexbin for a high score. The number of leftover CC and CD are counted negatively against the user score. The user must relocate these items with a care for accuracy because it is not guaranteed that attempting to put the item into the hexbin will result in the item reaching inside the hexbin. An inaccurate throw may knock a ball off the shelf and into the hexbin, this must be avoided. The pencils must leave the drawer, but must not make it into the hexbin. The user is free to relocate them elsewhere. All CC,CD and pencils left in the drawer will count negatively towards the user score. All CC and CD that are out of the top drawer, but not in the hexbin will count negatively towards the user score. This equation will determine the final score: (CC+CD)-3(sum($#balls_in_bin + $#CC_not_in_bin_but_not_in_drawer + $#CD_not_in_bin_but_not_in_drawer + $#CC_leftover_top + $#CD_leftover_top + $#pencil_leftover_top)).
overall: It is hard to say because I do not understand the role that pencils play in the game, and I feel that they are a massive hole in my understanding. For the game itself, it reminds me of something I might cook up in my head as I sat around an unopened text book the night before an exam. Distracted by the need to procrastinate, but unwilling to become distracted with electronics. The items sound like I looked around for whatever was available and just made up some rules as I played a few test rounds, challenging myself slightly more each time with more specific, but seemingly arbitrary rules.

explain: The user begins each level instructions to locate all of the credit cards (CC) and cmpact discs (CD) in the room and to relocate the items into the hexbin. One item will increase the points, and the other will decrease to an inverse number such that CC+CD=0. Each CC that is relocated to the hexbin must be balanced with a CD. There will likely be a set number of items the user must collect to complete the level. The gist of the instructions for the level will be to place all CC and CD into hexbin. The balanced score will allow the user to identify, potentially, whether a final unfound item is either a CC or CD through the score value relative to zero.
overall: This game feels like it would be suitable for a tutorial only. The game seems sufficiently redundant with the requirement only to walk between two locations, (a) location of item, (b) location of hexbin. And then repeat the process until all items are complete.

explain: The user is granted 1 point value for each iteration. One iteration involves retrieving a ball from the shelf, launching it towards a bedroom wall, and retrieving the ball prior to the ball hitting any surface. The user is granted one point and may repeat the process if the ball is caught and possession is maintained. If the user makes contact with the ball, but fails to maintain possession, the user is awarded one point, but the ball is no longer in play. The user has expired a full turn when all six balls are no longer in play.
overall: The game play instructions remind me of a game I played as a kid called wallball. The rules were similar, except dropping the ball lead to the removal of the player, so of like a last man standing. This seems like a variation of simply bouncing a ball off of a wall, except that there are two sizes and six balls to loose. Pretty generic, but also very effective for capturing the focus and attention of a player.

explain: The user must place the hexbin in the corner of the room that is not shown in the images above, where there must be a bedroom door. The bin must be rotated such that the shorter side is facing the wall and the tall side is facing the user. The user may select the specific location of the hexbin such that it is close enough to satisfy as being considered near the door. The user must identify an ideal placement such that the circumference of the topside of the hexbin is placed at a distanced from the wall so that it is possible to for a ball to land and remain wedged in place, without falling either into the hexbin or off the edge. The user has six balls to work with, but only the larger 3 balls are designated for a bonused score by landing the wedging attempt. Thus, a user will have an upper score limit of 18 (5+5+5+1+1+1). No score is given for balls that land only inside the hexbin. They must rest both on-top, and at least partially within the inner circumference of the opening.
overall: This game sounds like it is the result of many hours spent developing a simple boredom killing game into a feat of masterful precision. The objections are simple to understand, but I expect they are incredibly difficult to accomplish without first devoting a considerable chunk of time to practice. I imagine the final result would be something of a house of cards, except made from 6 balls. I have a lot of respect for this game design if, in fact, I have imagined it correctly.

explain: Place 30 chairs onto a desk and maintain motion of the chair. This should be possible with the rotational movement of the swivel topside section of the chairs. For each chair to is placed onto the desk, one point is awarded. The user must locate 30 chairs to receive 30 points. The level is complete when the user reaches 30 points.
overall: This game seems impossible to win. The environment provides only for 2 chairs, leaving a requirement gap of 28. This renders the level impossible to complete because not enough supplies are available to obtain the necessary points. It is possible that this is some kind of mental puzzle, and that perhaps by using a pair of mirrors, a reflection of the chair would satisfy the requirement, and thus providing a non-physical supply of chairs which can be perceived as being in motion on top of a desk. But I am not confident about this and so I feel it would be far more likely to be an impossible level to complete.

explain:
One point shall be awarded if a cube and a rectangle occupy the safe top surface of a cube one level below. 
Checker:
=>(Cube_Top+Rect_Top)/
Cube_Bottom 
==> return +1

One point shall be awarded when two cubes occupy the same top surface of a rectangle which rests on the top surface of a cube, if and only if, the rectangle and bottom cube share the same type classification. 
Checker:
=>(Cube_Top1+Cube_Top2) / 
Rect / 
Cube_Bottom 
==> if type(Rect) === type(Cube_Bottom) 
===> return +1

One point shall be awarded when one rectangle block rests on the top surface of a cube that rests on the topside of another cube, if and only if the two cube blocks share a type classification. 
Checker:
=> Rect / 
Cube_Middle / 
Cube_Bottom 
==> if type(Cube_Middle) === type(Cube_Bottom) 
===> return +1

The final user score will be the value of the total number of instances that each configuration is present at time of completion. There are no restrictions to limit the combining of such rules to indicate that the blocks are point independent and so the user may combine the shape combination requirements to maximize the score. For the purposes of the same, a block type should be considered as the color of the block such that a pair of common colored blocks will count as having the same type.
overall: It seems like the design was intending to accomplish a goal of being overly complicated. I do not want to speculate for the reasons, but I believe it would make for a good mental exercise for flexing the logic muscle. It would be able to occupy my interest, but would not make for a fun time for children. I could see some fun with a multiplayer version with a shared dialogue as a team building exercise. It would help to know whether my assumption about the type matching is correct with my guess that color reflects a block type. Otherwise it would be impossible for a cube and a rectangle to share a type, because a cube cannot be a rectangle.

explain: The user may attempt to move credit cards (CC) and compact discs (CD) into the hexbin while a cube-block is in motion. A cube block is considered in motion so long as the item has  a changing position and that the block has been released into the environment by the user. One point shall be awarded fro each CC or CD inside the hexbin, and one point shall be deducted for each thrown block which has come to rest.
overall: As I understand the instructions, the game has a shortcut available if the user can somehow spin the top section of the office chairs prior to throwing and then toss the cube such that it lands on the flat top side of the now rotating office chair. The task will be quite difficult to start out, but I expect that it is a very steep learning curve and can be picked up without too much practice. From there, it is a simple race against the forces of gravity to relocate all the CC and CD into the hexbin. It is not clear if the transfers must happen one item at a time or if bulk movements are possible.

explain: The user must relocate one of the three larger balls so that the resting spot is on the top level of either the shelf behind the hexbin or the shell above the bed. The user has 30 seconds for their attempts. The user may or may not retrieve a missed attempt if time remains after completing the first three attempts.
overall: There is much left to the unknown and I feel that my opinions of the game depend a lot on the outcome of the accuracy of my guesses. I would like the game more if it was a matter of precision rather than speed. In this case, the user would end their turn after three throws regardless of additional time left on the 30 second timer. I expect that the rapid component of the game could add for excitement, but I feel it would be more challenging to go with the precision route. The starting point matters very much as well, given that there are two possible target landings on adjacent walls and nearly opposite sides. The points would be the same for each, but it would add a second layer of complexity to the game.

explain: The user will gain one point for every item that is stacked onto the bed and is not a pillow. No points are deducted for pillows on the bed, but no additional points will be awarded.
overall: This seems like it could be more of a pain to tally up points that to complete the task. It would definitely be an extremely effective way to become familiar with every object in the environment. But it seems like an easy task to conquer once the room is entirely relocated upon the bed.

explain: Relocate the hexbin to either an area on the bed or next to a wall and keep it in place for the entirety of the game. Three points will be awarded for each dodgeball that rests inside of the hexbin, having made its way without touching the floor. One point will be awarded for each dodgeball that rests inside of the hexbin, having made its way after a floor bounce.
overall: It seems dull. I suppose the challenge can be increased by maximizing the distance between the user and the hexbin, but the room is limited in size. I would think a bounced shot would be more difficult and therefore more deserving of points. There is not much interaction with the room items apart from the three dodgeballs and single hexbin.

explain: The idea of the game is to start off by placing red pyramids on the a rug where they must remain in place during the game, during the main part of the game you will engage in activities such as throwing cube blocks, placing yellow cube boxes in buildings, or stacking yellow cube boxes on top of each other.  You will earn points with each number of correctly stacked blocks.
overall: It is an interesting game , it's quite skill based with the potential for enjoyment and competitiveness .

explain: The main aim of this game is to throw balls aiming to get them inside of a hexagonal bin, with the goal that they stop moving once inside. the game concludes once 6 or more points have been scored or after 15 throw attempts. You get 1 point for each ball you manage to stop moving inside the hexagonal bin.
overall: It seems a very basic and straight forward styled game, it's simplicity would appeal to a variety of people and it could be quite challenging

explain: You will stat by placing a hexagonal bin near the door and make sure it remains there for the whole game. The aim is to throw dodgeballs so that they roll on the rug and come to a stop on the hexagonal bin, you will get 1 point for each ball you throw and an extra 5 points for each ball you manage to have stop on the bin.
overall: An original game with an odd game play,  but it seems quite challenging and thought provoking.

explain: The basic set up involves placing a hexagonal bin near the rug and having it remain there during the entire game,  you will proceed to move chairs onto desks and place teddy bears on desks but make sure you dont position them diagonally. you will earn 80 points for each chair placed on  a desk and 1 point for each teddy bear that is NOT positioned diagonally.
overall: It seems quite complicated and not easy to follow along with,  a lot strategic thinking would be required to try pull the game off.

explain:
You will need to place a curved wooden ramp near the center of the room,  you will need to make sure it stays there the entire game. 
The name of the game is to hold a pink dodgeball while facing the ramp and aim to throw the dodgeball so that it touches the ramp , you will observe if the dodgeball either lands on the bed or comes to a stop and touches you without holding onto it. 
scoring is based on the number of times the dodgeball lands on the bed  minus the number of times the dodgeball stopped and touched you.
overall: It's certainly very unique in it's style and would be quite challenging to pull off.

explain: You will throw dodgeballs around the room and get 1 point for each thrown and you will lose 3 points for each that happens to land inside a doggie bed
overall: An extremely easy game with very little skill to pull off.

explain:
The main idea of the game involves throwing dodgeballs so that they land either inside a doggie bed or a hexagonal bin. 
you will end up with 1 point for each dodgeball that lands on a doggie bed, or a hexagonal bin or simply stops moving after a thrown dodgeball regardless of where it lands.
overall: It's a simple yet versatile game, by having different targets you get some variety to keep it interesting

explain:
You will simply throw dodgeballs so they land either inside or on top of a hexagonal bin. 
1 point is scored for each ball that stops moving while inside or on top of the bin
overall: A very, straightforward game but has the potential to be pretty engaging and challenging to do time and time again

explain:
The main idea is to move objects so they are not moving and get them close to the rug as possible, 
you have 3 minutes to complete this task and will get 1 point for each object that is not moving and is placed near the rug once the time is up
overall: It offers a complex challenge within a short time frame,  it requires quick execution but didn't make a whole lot of sense.

explain:
You are required to ensure NO blocks remain on any shelves while being able to create a building with exactly six objects . the challenge is to ensure all blocks are either in this building or match a block within it but NOT be identical .
You will first hold blocks without placing them inside any building 
take time to interact with the blocks by holding or moving them so they touch at some point
when ready you will throw the block 
the idea by the end of the game is to make sure no two blocks in the initial set up are not stacked on each other UNLESS they are from the initial non set up building 
you will get 5 points for each object deemed unique  and gain 100 points if there happens to be a building from the initial set up and one that is NOT.  you will lose 10 points for each time a block is thrown that was inside a non set up building
overall: A very overly complex game with a lot of moving parts. Very challenging and difficult to learn but quite unique and would be very thought provoking.

explain: The object of the game seems to be to stack three blocks on top of a tall rectangular block using at least two blocks that are the same type as the tall one. In terms of scoring, your score is 1.4x the number of stacks made by the end of the game.
overall: I don't really see how this game can be fun. The object of the game seems a bit dull and boring, and there isn't much point to the game. I also don't see how it poses any challenge.

explain: The object of the game seems to be to score 10 points or more by moving chairs and not having them move when you've let go.. You get 1 more each time you do that, and 4 points if the chair ends up on a desk and is not moving.
overall: I have to say this game does not seem very realistic and feels like a real stretch. The object of the game seems a bit pointless and not very fun or motivating.

explain: The object of the game is to move objects that are not pillows onto the bed. You get 1 point for each different object that is not a pillow that you put on the bed.
overall: While this game is very easy to understand and seems easy to play, it doesn't seem very fun. There is no challenge to finding non-pillow objects to put on the bed after all.

explain: The object of the game is to throw golf balls, basketballs and dodgeballs and have them land and stop on different targets. The scoring depends on what type of ball you throw and where it lands. You also need a hexagonal bin as one of the targets to throw things onto.
overall: This seems like a more reasonable game that could be fun and is pretty easy to understand. The main weird thing that stands out is that the scoring is so variable, ranging from 1 to 40 points. Given that, it seems like there is no point in trying to score one point at a time.

explain: The object of the game is to place chairs on desks and throw basketballs such that they land atop the hexagonal bin. For the former, you get 1 point, and for the latter, you get 40 points.
overall: This seems like a bit of a weird variation of game 4. Again, it seems weird that the scoring is so variable from 1 point to 40 points.

explain: The object of the game is to throw a dodgeball so that it lands and stops on a hexagonal bin. Each time you succeed, you get 1 point.
overall: I think this game is pretty straightforward and easy to understand. I think it poses a reasonable challenge and sort of feels like a version of basketball.

explain: The object of the game is to place balls on the bed. For each different ball you have placed on the bed, you will receive one point.
overall: I think this game is very simple and straightforward, if not that creative or interesting. It seems like a game so easy even children would find it too easy.

explain: The object of the game is to move chairs so they end up on desks and are still moving. Each time you succeed, you get 1 point (if it's still moving by the end of the game). The game ends once 30 points have been scored.
overall: Overall, while I understand the object of the game, I find it a bit silly and chaotic to need to keep all the chairs in motion. It seems like it would be a rather hectic game.

explain: The object of the game is to stack different types of blocks atop one another. For each set of blocks you have successfully stacked according to the listed criteria, you receive 10 points at the end of the game.
overall: I understand the nature of this game, but it is unclear when the game ends. For example, is it when you reach a certain number of points?

explain: The object of the game is to throw dodgeballs at different targets like the side table, bed, and hexagonal bin. You get 1 point for each successful attempt of getting the ball to land on the different targets and stop moving.
overall: I understand the game and it feels pretty straightforward. However, it is unclear when the game ends, and if it is based on scoring a certain number of points.

explain: Hold one of the balls and throw it aiming for the hexagonal bin. You will score one point for each ball that makes it into the bin. The game ends once you've scored at least six points or made 15 attempts to throw.
overall: Seems pretty simple! It's a shoot-the-ball-into-the-hoop type game using more mundane items.

explain: You hit the ball against the wall repeatedly, either catching the ball as it bounces or hitting it back against the wall similar to a game played as kids.
overall: It reminds me of the game "wallball" where you essentially play a game with pong against the wall with a hi-bounce ball.

explain: Begin by placing a dodgeball near the desk. Throw the dodgeball so that it touches the south wall while in motion but do not hold the dodgeball (or teddy bear?) while the ball is in motion. To score a point, the ball must touch the south wall and then stop moving.
overall: I'm not really sure what the point of this game is, actually? The description isn't clear enough for me to get an idea of how this game would be played.

explain: Throw dodgeballs at target (side table, bed, hexagonal bin), score one point each time the ball lands in or on the target.
overall: Seems relatively straightforward, assuming I've understood the description given.

explain: To set up the game, place a curved wooden ramp next to the hexagonal bin. Throw the dodgeball so that it rolls up the curved wooden ramp and lands into the bin. Score a point for each ball that makes it into the bin.
overall: Reminds me of skiball, I think. A simplified version with one target.

explain: Throw dodgeballs into the hexagonal bin, each ball that makes it into the bin scores a point. There also seems to be a component of the game played with the blocks that also involves points, but the description is too vague for me to really get the point of the blocks.
overall: I'm not really sure what the point of the blocks are with this game.

explain: Throw the dodgeballs around the room, score a point for every dodgeball thrown but lose three if the dodgeball lands within the doggie bed.
overall: Sounds almost too simple to be any fun as a game.

explain: To setup, place bin on the rug. Throw the dodgeball so that it lands within the bin. Score a point for each successful throw that lands within the bin.
overall: Seems similar to other games described, nothing really different other than placing the bin on the rug first.

explain: To set up, place bin near the door. Put credit cards or cds in the bins and throw the white gold balls at the bin. Score a point for each throw and 40 for each credit card or CD you put in the bin.
overall: Again, not really sure what the point of the additional items are in this game or how they're used.

explain: Throw dodgeballs so that they land on the top shelf, score one point for each ball that lands on the shelf. Game ends after 30 seconds.
overall: Seems pretty simple, but boring. Possibly difficult if only because the balls are likely to roll off the shelf.

explain: Pick up and move chairs onto desks, spinning them so they move without you holding them. You get more points if the chair is moving without holding them.
overall: The game does not make much sense. Why do you get a point if the chair stops moving if the object of the game is to keep them moving? What is the purpose of putting the chairs on desks?

explain: Throw cube blocks, you get a point for each block that you throw.
overall: It is a very simplistic game. The only objective is to throw cube blocks. Seems like it would get boring very fast, and there isn't really any skill involved. Anyone can throw cube blocks.

explain: You have to throw dodgeballs into bins and doggie beds. You get 1 point for making it in either of them.
overall: It's similar to a lot of games that most people have probably played at some point in there life, throwing balls into a target or goal. Obviously Basketball is the most famous of these games.

explain: Throw teddy bears at pillows 10 times, for each bear that lands on a pillow you get one point.
overall: The game is very simple and easy to understand, although it does not seem that fun to play.

explain: Throw dodgeballs into the bin, the score is the amount of throws that you make plus 70% of the throws that landed in the bin.
overall: I do not understand the scoring rules for this game, why is the number of times you throw the ball at the bin worth more than the number of times you actually successfully threw the ball in the bin? One player could shoot 10 times and make it every time and get a final score of 17 while another could shoot it 18 times and miss every time and still win the game.

explain: Throw dodgeballs across the room towards the hexagonal bin 5 times, whoever throws it directly in the bin the most wins.
overall: It seems like a fun game, similar to the other basketball like games. It's interesting that it limits you to 5 throws, so you really have to make each throw count.

explain: Throw dodgeballs towards the doggie bed or hexagonal bin, trying to land them on or in the bed and bin. You get 1 point for both of those scenarios.
overall: Another basketball like game. I don't understand why the doggie bed is a target, it seems strange because it isn't shaped like a typical bucket you would throw things into like the hexagonal bin is.

explain: Put chairs on top of desks and throw basketballs on top of the bin. You get 40 points if you get it on top of the bin and 1 point for each chair you put on the desk.
overall: The scoring in this game does not make much sense. Why would you try to put the chair on the desk if landing the basketball on the bin is worth 40x as many points?

explain: Throw a dodgeball, when it comes to a stop you get one point.
overall: The game makes no sense. There is no way to lose because the dodgeball will always come to a stop eventually after you throw it, so you will always get a point.

explain: Stand next to the bin, throw balls into the bin, the game will stop when you make a ball into the bin or when you throw 5 balls, whichever comes first. You get 5 points when you throw the ball in the bin.
overall: Why does the game stop as soon as you make 1 ball? Also, standing directly next to the bin makes the game far too easy to play.

explain: It sounds kind of like a simplified ski ball
overall: The description is a little lacking and confusing.  From the pictures, I cannot visualize how to play.

explain: Bedroom basketball.  This is the same as a door mounted mini basketball hoop.
overall: A classic game, not original at all.

explain: This is extremely hard to understand from the description.  It sounds like you just bounce the ball off of the wall and get a point.

explain: This is basically basketball again.  The phrasing of the rules is just different.

explain: This is once again bedroom basketball.  "Stops moving" is effectively the same phrasing as "lands in".  You throw the ball into the bin for a point.

explain: First, a person should gather all the golf balls, dodgeballs, along with the triangle and pyramid blocks by the side table.  Then put the desk chair to the side.  Set up the curved wooden ramp, with it's front toward the front of the desk.  Put the bin at the bottom of the ramp.  The aim of this game is to score by throwing the objects towards the desk.  Points are earned for each object thrown.  Additional points can be earned if a golf ball touches the ramp before landing.  A point will be deducted if an object touches the computer.
overall: I thought this game was a lot.  The instructions are complicated and may be for older kids or adults.

explain: You can choose to place the hexagonal bin on the bed or next to a wall, but make sure it stays there the entire time. explain: Put one of the curved ramps made from wood next to the rug and don't move it. Retrieve a beach ball and throw it on the ramp so it can roll toward the rug. The goal is to make it stop on the rug and depending on what color the ball stops on, your points will either increase or decrease. Points are as follows: Pink= 1 point, Yellow= 2 points, Orange= 3 points, Green= 3 points, Purple= 4 points, and White= -1 point
