explain: You are supposed to put different objects in specific areas/locations around the room.  You are also throwing balls to land in a hexagonal shaped bin.
overall: Mostly it sounds incredibly boring to me.  Placing an object and throwing a ball.  Very remedial, there's no point, no real challenge.

explain: You have to move chairs so they are up on desks AND moving at the same time or they keep moving.  You win when you get 30 points, that's 1 chair per point.
overall: The game seems pointless and boring.  The idea of keeping chairs in motion on the desk is nonsensical.  The room would also have to be far larger to accommodate all the chairs - unless they were tiny toy chairs?

explain: You have to throw a red ball into a hexagonal shaped bin without the ball touching the floor.  Before this you have to place a triangle shaped ramp near the bins, but I'm not sure if you have to use the ramp? The game ends after 10 tries and you get points based on various criteria.
overall: The game is confusing  both the game and the scoring - it's unclear if you are supposed to USE the ramp or just place it?  Also, it's really just throwing a ball into a bin.  Boring. Also, the scoring scheme makes no sense.

explain: You have to put chairs on desks, put pends or CDS (or both) into a hex bin, throw balls onto a bed and the stack blocks in the correct way. You get a high score by doubling the amount of things you did.
overall: Overall super boring - I'm sorry to sound like a broken record.  This might be a game for toddlers?  There's really no challenge or anything interesting about it.

explain: You have to move objects (which?) to a rug and a door. You have to break some objects.  The scoring is based nonsensical.
overall: Totally ambiguous - what objects should be broken, which need to go by the door or on the rug?  The scoring system is nonsensical and overly complex at the same time.   Who wants to calculate .7 of objects?

explain: You stand next to a hex bin and throw the ball in.  You get 5 tries.  As soon as you get a ball in you get 5 points and the game is over.
overall: There's no "there" there.   There's no game per say.  You "win" by getting a ball in, get 5 points and the game is over.   There's no motivation to keep playing, so the scoring system is pointless.

explain: In this game you throw two kinds of balls into a bin and you are aiming to get balls IN the bin and top of the bin, you get 1 point for each.
overall: The scoring system is deeply flawed and pretty much impossible.   Impossible to get a ball to land on TOP of an open bin and even if you managed that feat, you only get 1 extra point.   The game would be repetitive and boring.

explain: You throw balls into a hex bin and doggie bed.  You get 1 point for each on that lands in either place.
overall: This would be very monotonous and repetitive.  There's no variation or skill involved other than throwing.  There would be no interest to keep playing after 20 seconds.

explain: You place any object that is NOT a pillow on the bed and you get points for each non-pillow item on the bed when the game ends.
overall: Overly simplistic, geared more toward a toddler and not at all engaging.   Just a repetitive action over and over.  No challenge, very uninteresting.

explain: You put a hex bin near a rug and throw objects in a doggie bed or in the bin.   You get points for landing in the doggie bed, the bin or just because you threw it and it eventually stopped moving.
overall: This isn't a game, it's just throwing stuff.  You get a point for everything you throw since everything will eventually stop moving, so there's not even motivation to throw the ball INTO the bin or doggie bed.   Pointless.

explain: You throw credit cards and dodge balls into a hexagonal bin. 40 points for every ball you throw in the bin times the number of credit cards you throw in the bin, plus 1 point for every ball that doesn't make it into the bin.
overall: It is a game I would play if I were super bored.

explain: throw all the cube blocks you see in the room and get 1 point for each different cube you throw.
overall: It is just throwing cubes.

explain: Throw the dodgeball and hit the south wall. Do that repeatedly and don't touch any teddy bears or pick up any moving balls. The ball must not be moving when you pick it up.
overall: It is like an average game a kid would play.

explain: Take everything that is not a pillow and put it on the bed as quickly as you can. You get 1 point for every non-pillow item you put on the bed at the end of the game.
overall: Pretty simple game.

explain: Throw dodgeballs and you lose 3 points if they land on a doggie bed or gain 1 point if they don't land on a doggie bed.
overall: This is a simple game to play if your bored.

explain: Stand on a rug and throw 10 balls into a hexagonal bin. For each ball that stops moving inside the bin, you get 1 point.
overall: This is a simple game that could be played if you were bored.

explain: Throw dodgeballs in the room. If it lands inside or on a doggie bed you lose 3 points and if it lands and stops outside of a doggie bed you gain 1 point.
overall: It is very similar to another game that was just described.

explain: Throw balls at a hexagonal bin. the game ends when you get 6 balls to land in the hexagonal bin and stop moving or after you have throw 15 balls. You get 1 point for every ball that lands in the bin and stops moving, so 6 possible points.
overall: The game makes me think of basketball a little.

explain: If you place a credit card or cd in a hexagonal bin you get 1 point. If you throw a cube block and it comes to a stop you loose 1 point. So, only place credit cards and cd's into a hexagonal bin to win the most points.
overall: I think this game isn't that great.

explain: You have to get 30 points to end the game. You have to put 30 chairs on a desk and keep them all in motion at the same time to end the game and you will get 30 points.
overall: This game sounds impossible to play.

explain: putting a bin on the rug while keeping it there to throw a dodgeball inside it and points will be scored for each successful throw inside the bin
overall: I believe and think it will be a very fun game to play

explain: placing a hexagonal bin and keeping it on the rug then you put a cellphone orCDs into the bin to score 2 points
overall: I believe this game will be very fun and enjoyable

explain: moving the chairs till they end up been on desk and in motion and get a point for each chair on desk. The game ends after scoring more than 30 points
overall: the game is very creative and will help with interacting with the environment

explain: make sure the top drawer is empty and place different objects in it to earn a point
overall: very cool game to help interacting more with virtual environment

explain: place a credit card into the hexagonal bin but no point will be scored
overall: a very nice and  interesting game to play

explain: place a hexagonal bin near the rug and throw dodgeballs and tan cylindrical blocks inside and beside the bin.
overall: a very nice and  interesting game to play

explain: to score 40 points, you have to throw dodge balls into a hexagonal bin
overall: a very nice and  interesting game to play and help understand ones environment

explain: throwing of golfballs and basketball into an hexagonal bin to score a point
overall: a very nice and  interesting game to play

explain: place objects on the bed but not a pillow
overall: a very nice and  interesting game to play

explain: The game involves throwing teddy bears onto pillows. You get a point for each one that lands & stays on a pillow.  The game ends after 10 pillows have been thrown.
overall: It seems OK.  Might be fun for a short while.

explain: You pick up & throw cube blocks and get a point for throwing each one.
overall: It's not much of a game.  It would be like if you scored points every time you kicked a soccer ball.

explain: You throw a ball into a hexagonal bin and place credit cards and CDs various places.
overall: It's kind of confusing.  There doesn't seem to be much strategy,

explain: You try to throw golf balls and dodgeballs into or on top of a bin.
overall: It would be fun, but some of the rules seem unrealistic, like getting a dodgeball inside the bin or having a golf ball sit on top of the bin.

explain: You move objects near the rug and get 1 point for each one.
overall: It's not much of a game. You just move things and place them next to a rug.

explain: You try to throw a dodgeball into a bin without it touching the floor.
overall: It doesn't make much sense. The gameplay says the ball is not supposed to touch the floor, but you get points if it goes in the bin regardless.

explain: Throw a dodgeball and try to get them to land on a bed, side table, or on top of a bin.
overall: It's ok.  It would be challenging to get the ball to stay on a table, but much easier on a bed.

explain: Throw dodgeballs so they land on a doggie bed or on top of a bin.
overall: It's a lot like many of the other games described here. Not much new.

explain: Try to throw dodgeballs into a bin, doggie bed, or simply have the ball stop moving.
overall: It's kind of dumb.  The ball will stop moving each time so there's no skill.

explain: Try to throw various objects in a bin, while avoiding any computers.
overall: It seems like it would be challenging to some degree. The point system is unique.

explain: In this game you will be stacking blocks one upon another, kind of like building a tower. the blocks must be stacked in the proper order. Start with a bridge block first. Place a flat block on the bridge block, then a tall cylindrical block on the flat block, then a cube on top of the cylinder & top it all off with a pyramid block. You get 10 points for each set of blocks you succesfully stack in this order.
overall: this seems like a fun way to learn to manipulate objects in a virtual environment. I think I would enjoy trying this game out & I would definitely need things like this to help me learn how to properly utilize a new virtual space.

explain: Throw dodgeballs around the room but be careful not to let them land in a doggie bed. You'll get 1 point for every ball thrown but you lose 3 points if a ball lands in a doggie bed.
overall: This one could be a bit tricky. You have to learn how trajectories work in this environment fairly quickly and then apply it immediately considering the scoring rules.

explain: Place a hexagonal bin near the rug & make sure it stays there for the duration of the game.  Now, throw a dodgeball in such a way that it lands on top of the hexagonal bin & stays there. You get one point every time you successfully land a ball on top of the bin & it stays.
overall: This could be really difficult. I'm not sure I could pull this off. In real life it would be extremely difficult. Not sure how it would work in a virtual environment but it is a good way to learn the physics of said environment.

explain: Using a tall rectangular block as a base, stack 2 more tall rectangular block & a third block of your choice on top of it. Order doesn't seem to matter just as long as they stay stacked on top of the initial tall rectangular block. Your score will be 1.4 time the number of successful stacks you have at the end of the game.
overall: This is another excellent game for learning to manipulate objects in a virtual space & for learning  the physics of it.

explain: Throw a dodgeball. You get 1 point for each throw once the ball comes to a stop.
overall: This one seems super easy on the surface. I kind of wonder if there's not something I'm unaware of that might make it more challenging.

explain: Place a hexagonal bin by the door and make sure it remains there throughout the game. Put credit cards or Cds in the bin and throw white golf balls into the bin. You get one point for each golf ball thrown, once it has come to a stop and 40 points for each credit card or Cd put inside the bin.
overall: This is a strange sounding game that makes little sense on the surface. Maybe I'm missing something but it really doesn't sound much like a game at all.

explain:
Place a dodgeball near the desk at least once during game setup.
To play, hold a dodgeball and throw it. You get 1 point for each thrown dodgeball once it comes to a stop
overall: This is another strange game that doesn't seem like a game. It doesn't make much sense at all.

explain: Throw balls so that they stop moving 7 land inside a hexagonal bin. The game ends once you've scored 6 or more points or after you've made at least 15 throw attempts. You get 1 point for each ball that ends up inside the bin when it stops moving.
overall: This seems to be another confusing one that makes little sense. I mean throw the ball in the bin I get & ok it could be fun but I'm not entirely sure that's the whole goal.

explain: Throw dodgeballs and place credit cards & CDs in a bin. You get 40 points for each dodgeball that ends up in the bin multiplied by the number of credit cards or CDs in the bin plus 1 point for each ball thrown.
overall: I'm very confused by the placing of credit cards or CDs into the bin. I don't understand that.

explain: place a hexagonal bin near the center of the room. Place objects into the bin or set them in motion so they end up in the bin. You get 1 point for each object you successfully move into the bin.
overall: Yet another with putting objects into a bin. I'm guessing maybe that's harder than it sounds on the surface?

explain: You basically pick up blocks off of a rug and toss them. Your scoring will depend on the number of different blocks that are thrown by the time the game is terminated.
overall: I think it would make for a fun time killer. This would probably make for a good "on the go" phone game.

explain: First find the rug. Next, place the garbage can shaped like a hexagon near the rug. Make sure the can remains there throughout game play. You will next grab some dodgeballs. Your objective is to land the balls either in or on top of the hexagonal bin, on top of the desk or on the bed. You earn a point for landing the ball on any of these objects. Your final score is determined by the number of balls landed.
overall: I think it would be challenging. I could see myself having fun playing this many times in succession.

explain: Stand next to the desk, and move a variety of things on or off the bed. 5 points are gained for placing said objects on either the doggie bed, the chair or the laptop. 1 point is earned from objects that land on the bed and stay, but aren't the 3 previously mentioned objects. 5 points are deducted for objects that don't stay on the bed.
overall: I think this would be a good skill game, to test eye/hand coordination.

explain: Throw balls into the garbage bin, and then place CDs, pencils and credit cards into the bin or the top desk drawer. Score depends on the number CDs and credit cards in the bin. Points deducted are 3 times the amount of balls in the garbage bin, the number of CDs, credit cards and pencils in the top drawer, and how many CDs and cards didn't make it into the bin.
overall: I think this would be rather tedious. Keeping track of what to put where would get old fast, I would think.

explain: Move objects onto the rug, including dodgeballs. Throw the balls so they land on top of the garbage bin. 1 point is earned for each ball that makes it on top of the bin. 70 points may be earned for the number of objects that are still near the rug, which is multiplied by the number of ball remaining on the rug.
overall: This game would be fun to play sporadically, say on a rainy day or lunch break. It doesn't involve too much deep stratagy.

explain: Pick up the cubes. Throw them or gently set them down. Pick them up again and place them down again. Try to do this without any movement. 1 point for every block you throw, and 15 for putting it down, lifting it again and placing it down with no movement.
overall: This game seems kinda boring. There's no real challenge to it. Also, repetitive, in a non challenging way.

explain: Place the bin next to the door, and make sure it stays there for the duration of the game. Move objects so they are still and near the rug. Throw the balls so that they are still when they land or land on top of the bin and stay still
overall: The instructions are really hard to follow. I'm sure it would be fun, but has a learning curve to some degree.

explain: Place the bin in close proximity to the top shelf. It will stay there for the duration of the game. Pick up, hold and release green triangles, throw dodgeballs onto the bin and throw the cube blocks in general. Score depends on how many times the green triangles have been  picked up, dropped and picked up again. Also, the number of times you've thrown the cube blocks, as well as thrown one in motion. Finally, the number of times you've thrown a ball onto the bin and stays counts for the same point amount.
overall: The instructions don't seem to make a whole lot of sense. I can sense it would take a while to get the hang of this game.

explain: Pick up the cubes and place them inside the buildings, and either remove them or leave them. Game terminates when you've handled any cube 3 or so times. points are dependent on how many times put a cube in a building and it was removed or the gam ends.
overall: The game sems simple enough. I can see myself growing bored with it rather quickly however.

explain: Put a chair in the center of the room. It can't face the desk or the bed. It must stay there for the entirety of the game. Stand next to the bed and throw dodgeballs onto the bed on to the chair, into the bin or other locations in the room. 5 points for each ball that lands in the bin, and 1 each for the bed and the chair. 1 point is subtracted for it landing elsewhere in the room. You then add up your points to determine your score. The game terminates after you earn 10 or more points.
overall: This game sounds like it would be quite involved, but in a good way. It would keep me occupied for quite a while.

explain: A shooting game where the goal is to shoot the ball so that the balls end up either in the hexagon bin or the dog bed. Each ball scored has equal points so there is not benefit to one over the other.
overall: I think this is a more fun two player game where each goal is for one player... or where there is some difference between each goal- the fact the each goal scores the same amount is a problem to me.

explain: The goal of this game is to get chairs on the desk and in motion. The goal is to score thirty points, which requires a lot of chairs on the desk and in motion at the end of the game.
overall: I don't understand this game. It seems like it requires thirty chairs, when I only see 2 chairs. I don't understand what it means but moving these chairs to the desk and have them be in motion, and have them stay in motion to score points. I don't understand the goal of the game, so It would be hard to play.

explain: This is a shooting game where different kinds of balls score different points, and how close you get to the goal you are also effects points. If you use diffferent balls, and get closer you score more, while you you use a larger ball and land further away you score less..
overall: This seems like a reasonably fun game given the constraints of the room and would be a good way to pass time.

explain: Try to get as many doge-balls to land and stop on the top shelf in 30 seconds after player throws them on to the shelf.
overall: This feels like a think I would do when I was a kid when I was trying to pass the time. A little meaningless game to pass the time that doesn't really matter to anyone but the player.

explain: A homemade version of skeeball where the curve ramp is used for the base and the hexagon bin is used in place of the main part of a skeeball game. The goal of this game is to roll balls up the ramp into the bin. However given the size of the bin this feels too easy.
overall: I think it is too easy. The difficulty in skeeball is the number of holes you have to shoot into, the size of the hexagon bin means that with enough force you will score everytime and this will limit the fun of this game.

explain: You place credit cards or CDs into the hexagonal bin. However, this does not change the score because the score cancels out so I don't understand what the win condition could be for this game or how it could ever end or progress.
overall: I don't see how there is any logic to this game. There is no way to score, or win. the score always stays the same as the scores cancels out. I don't understand this as a game or why this would be fun.

explain: Place non-pillow objects on the bed until the end of the game, and score one point for every non-pillow object on the bed at the end of the game.
overall: There is not constraint on this game, other than pillows. How long does it last? What makes it hard? There is no obstacle to overcame that makes this a game worth playing.

explain: A simple shooting game where you try to shoot the dodgeball into the hexagonal bin. Scoring one point each time you successfully shoot the ball into this goal.
overall: It is simple, but it makes sense. It would be more fun with a second player to play defense and/or a time constraint this would add levels to make the game more of a sport, but as it stands this is the kind of thing a person would do to pass time in this room.

explain: You throw the ball against the wall and then try to catch it or touch it after it touches the wall. You score a point for throwing the ball. A point for it hitting the wall, and a third point for getting the ball after it returns
overall: This is like something I would do when I was a kid. I would change the rules so you score more for grabbing the ball on return than just touching it because those shouldn't be worth the same amount.

explain: The blue cube clock is placed on the rug and then other objects are moved around the room. You score points based on objects that have not moved and are near the north wall or yellow and blue blocks are sandiwhced.
overall: I don't understand this game at all. Things are moving is ways that I can't conceptualize. I don't understand the scoring. I don't really get the game play. None of it makes sense to me.

explain: You throw dodgeballs and try to land them in the hexagonal bin. You can also place CDs and credit cards in the bin. You get a point for each dodgeball you throw and 40 points for every dodgeball that lands in the bin multiplied by the number of CDs and credit cards in the bin.
overall: I like this game. It's a little bizarre, but in a good way. With a little imagination, this game can be very enjoyable.

explain: You must stack matching blocks. After putting a bin near a wall, you can throw golf balls on or in it. Your final score is the amount of blocks you stacked but minus the number of golf balls you have on or in the bin multiplied by four.
overall: It doesn't make sense. The rules make it so that the player shouldn't aim to throw the golf balls in or on the bin at all.

explain: After putting the bin next to the rug, find CDs and cellphones and put them inside the bin for 2 points each.
overall: It's a basic hide-and-seek, but with cellphones. I can imagine a lot of players enjoying playing this.

explain: Put the bin near the rug, then throw dodgeballs to have as many as you can end up either on the desk or in the bin. Your score is every ball that remains on either of those 2 places.
overall: It would be fun and challenging. Not only do you have to land the ball in those places, but you need to make sure the previous balls don't get knocked off from the new ones you throw.

explain: You stand on the rug and throw 10 balls, trying to get them in the bin. Your score is however many balls end up inside the bin.
overall: It's nice and simple. This is a game many already are familiar with.

explain: Clear out the top drawer and put as many items in it as possible. You get a point for each item you fit in there.
overall: This one is the best so far. I can imagine player jamming things in there that maybe wouldn't fit, haha!

explain: You throw dodgeballs without landing them on the doggie bed. At the end of the game, you get a point for every ball that is still but lose 3 points for every ball that's on the doggie bed.
overall: This is a fun game with a little challenge with it. You can throw the balls as hard as you want. If one ends up on the dog's bed, you must throw another ball to knock it off of there.

explain: Put a green golf ball and a dodgeball near the door and stand by them. Make sure the golf ball don't move for the whole game. Then throw dodgeballs or other objects aiming for the bin. The game ends when you finish throwing 3 things or when you throw a dodgeball for the second time and it stops moving. You get 10 points for each thing you throw in the bin.
overall: This game seems rather short or that you need to keep too careful an eye on what you're doing. I think it will be easy for player to break the rules of this game.

explain: You get a point for each block you throw. Your score is however many blocks you threw by the end of the game.
overall: It is very, very simple but it sounds like some quick fun. Not much else to say. The rules are rather simple.

explain: Find credit cards, CDs, and pencils to either put inside the top drawer or inside the bin. You can also throw balls inside the bin. Your score at the end of the game is however many cards and CDs inside the bin MINUS the number of balls not in the bin, the number of credit cards and CDs that's not inside the bin or top drawer, and the pencils that aren't in the top drawer all multiplied by three.
overall: This game is rather complex.  There is really no incentive for the player to throw the ball inside the bin. Placing the CDs and cards are also a losing situation. At any point, a card or CD will not be in the top drawer (because it's in the bin) or not in the bin (because it's in the top drawer).

explain: First place a hexagonal bin near a door and leave there for the entire game.  Then throw dodge balls until it either lands in the bin or anywhere outside when the ball stops.
overall: Sounds simple but confusing at the same because of how the gameplay is described. I am not sure how I would be able to play this until I physically interacted with the game.

explain: First I place a hexagonal bin near a rug and keep it there for entire game. Then to score points I must either place chair on top of desk or make a basketball land on top of the bin. I make more points if it lands on the bin.
overall: It seems like fun game that would keep me entertain for awhile. I can also setup a competition to play with friends.

explain: The gameplay lasts 30 seconds and I must throw dodgeballs until they land and stop on top of the shelf. I receive 1 point for each dodgeball that stops on the shelf.
overall: Its a fun and simple game that I can play alone. Another good thing is that not a lot of things are needed to play.

explain: The game play is moving any objects near a rog and door and also breaking the objects. I gain points by either placing objects near the rug or door and broken objects.
overall: Seems like it can be boring as time passes because there is no challenge in playing the game. Maybe if it was versus someone, then it might become more interesting.

explain: The goal is to pick up the teddy bear from the chair and throw it. You get 5 points if the teddy bear lands in the bin and 1 point if it touches a ball. Place the ramp in the middle, the chair in front of it, and the ball near the bin.
overall: Seems like it can be a fun with friends. This can be challenging and entertaining.

explain: I pick up chairs and release them to make them move. You score 1 point each time a chair stops moving after you let it go. The game ends when your total score reaches 10 or more. You earn 4 points for each chair that ends up on a desk and is still moving at the end of the game.
overall: It can be a little confusing because of how the game play is described.

explain: Try to land the dodgeballs on either a dog bed or the hexagonal bin near a rug. You score points for each successful throw, and your final score is the total of these points.
overall: Sounds like it can a fun game to play by myself. Also not a lot things are needed to play.

explain: It's a game where you throw a ball, make it touch a wall, and then either catch it or touch it again. You earn 1 point for each successful throw, where the ball hits the wall, and you either catch it or touch it after its flight.
overall: It sounds very repetitive but sounds like it can very fun because I would be focus on not dropping the ball.

explain: You start with red pyramid blocks on a rug. The game involves picking up and throwing cube blocks, placing yellow cubes in buildings, and stacking blocks with a yellow cube on top of a matching block.
overall: Sounds like it can be fun but a little complicated. The scoring system is not that great.

explain: You start with an empty shelf and need to create a building with exactly six objects. Hold blocks without placing them, interact by moving them, and throw a block that was inside a building if you touch it while holding another. At the end, make sure blocks are stacked based on certain rules. Score points for unique objects held, bonus for specific building conditions, and lose points for throwing blocks from non-setup buildings.
overall: Seems like it can be a little complicated on how the gameplay is described. The scoring is also not great.

explain: To set up the game, I will place a dodgeball near the desk.  To play the game, I need to pick up a dodgeball and throw it.  I will get one point every time I throw a dodgeball and it comes to a stop.
overall: This game seems pretty simple.  However, it could be more difficult than it sounds if it is hard to move the ball or pick it up and throw it.

explain: I need to pick up some blocks and place them inside of a building of some sort.  Then I can take them out of the building or leave them there.  The game will end when I have picked up and put down the same block a minimum of three times.    The score is determined by how many times I have placed a block in the building.
overall: The game seems boring.  It could be challenging, though, if the blocks are difficult to manipulate.

explain: I need to find and pick up credit cards or CDs and place them in the hexagonal bin that is on the floor.  I will not score any points.  My score will remain zero.
overall: This game seems pointless, unless the point is to learn how to move and manipulate things in VR.  I think it would be boring.

explain: I need to move chairs, put them on the desk and set them in motion.  I will get one point for every chair that is on a desk and in motion at the end of the game.  The game will not end until I get a score of 30 or more.
overall: I think this game would be challenging.  I would have to figure out how to put the chairs on the desk and set them in motion.  I would have to figure out how to get to 30 points when there are only two chairs and one desk.

explain: I have to play with blocks by repeatedly picking them up, throwing them and putting them down.  I would get 15 points every time I picked up a block, set it down, picked it up again and set it down again without movement.  I would only get one point for throwing a block.
overall: This game could be fun if I could definitely figure out how to do it.  I'm not sure, though.

explain: I need to pick up objects in the room and put them on the bed.  I will get one point for every object on the bed that is not a pillow.
overall: I like this game.  It would be fun gathering up stuff from the room and putting it on the bed.  I would need to figure out if I should take the pillows off the bed.

explain: I need to pick up the hexagonal bin and put it near the rug.  Then I need to get a dodgeball, hold it and throw it in the bin.  I will get one point every time I get a dodgeball in the bin.
overall: I like this game.  It seems fun and challenging.

explain: I need to more object so that they are near the rug and the door.  I also need to break some objects.  The score depends on the number or objects I get near the door or near the rug and the number of broken objects.
overall: This game could be very fun.  I would have to figure out how to break objects, though.  That could be a challenge.

You will be scored based on how many chairs and teddy bears that are not positioned diagonally at the end of the game. explain: The objective of the game is to throw dodgeballs while avoiding throwing any dodgeballs inside of the doggie bed. For every dodgeball that is thrown that successfully avoid the doggie bed, the player will get 1 point, however every dodgeball that lands inside of the doggie bed loses the player 3 points.
overall: The game seems very uninteresting and almost dumb, there are no rules about what direction the ball can be thrown, how the ball must be thrown, and with a small doggie bed being the only target to avoid, it would seem like the simplest way to win the game would be to just lightly toss the ball in the opposite direction to the doggie bed. On top of this, there is no terminal to the game, so the player would just continue throwing balls for no reason until they get bored (which would probably be quick).

explain: The objective of this game is to toss balls into a hexagonal bin. You get 15 attempts to throw the ball inside of the bin, and win if you score 6 or more points.
overall: This game just seems like any of the million games that exist to put a ball inside of a goal. The rules don't specify what distance the player must be from the bin so I'd imagine I could just stand right above the bin and toss them directly in. Also, the numbers of 6 makes in 15 attempts seem pretty arbitrary.

explain: To play this game, you need to place a dodgeball near a desk, then pick up the dodgeball and throw it. Points are scored anytime the dodgeball is thrown and then comes to a stop.
overall: This game seems pretty ridiculous. The point of the game is to throw a ball, and you get points when the ball stops. One would assume that all balls that are thrown eventually stop, so the object of the game isn't even to make sure the balls stop moving, it is to simply throw a ball. I don't see any redeeming or appealing qualities about this game, other than potentially finding the act of throwing a ball fun.

explain: This game seems similar to bowling or golf, in that the objective is to roll a ball and have it land on a hexagonal bin. Once a ball is thrown, the player earns 1 point, however if the dodgeball lands or stops on the bin, the player earns an additional 5 points.
overall: This game doesn't seem very fun. Your objective is to roll a ball near a bin. That's it. I guess it could be interesting to see if you can roll the ball in different ways, or try to get the ball on a certain side of the bin, but as it stands, the game seems very boring.

explain: The goal of the game is to throw three different types of balls onto specific targets. Each time a golfball is thrown on a hexagonal bin, the player gets 1 point, each time a basketball is thrown on top of the top drawer, the player gets 40 points, and each time a player simultaneously throws a white golfball on top of the top drawer, a basketball on the hexagonal bin and a dodgeball on a hexagonal bin, the player scores 40 points.
overall: The game seems very complicated, with various ways of scoring points, however the difference in points for throwing a golfball on the bin as opposed to the other targets that award 40 points seems like a very simple strategy would quickly be made to achieve the easiest shot for the most amount of points.

explain: After placing a hexagonal bin in the center of the room, the player must move different objects into the bin, and earn 1 point for each unique object that is successfully placed in the bin.
overall: This just seems like a baby game to get them to clean up their toys, just place every object you see inside of the bin and hope most of them are unique. Maybe the game could be improved if the player is penalized for every duplicate object that is put into the bin.

explain: After positioning a curved ramp near the center of the room facing the bed, the objective is to roll the ball over the ramp and then land on the bed in order to earn points, however if the ball doesn't land on the bed and instead comes to a stop and touches the player, the player loses points. The final score is determined by subtracting the number of times the dodgeball successfully landed on the bed by the number of times the ball missed the bed and touched the player
overall: I guess the game seems interesting, you want to roll the ball over the ramp at a certain speed or strength so that it lands on the bed and doesn't overshoot, however I'm confused about the ball stopping and touching the player, is the ball gravitated towards the player so that it always comes back and touches them if they miss the bed?

explain: The objective of the game is to stack different types of blocks, earning 6 points for each stack at the end of the game. The player must stack a cube shaped block and a flat block on top of a black that is the same type as the cube block.
overall: The game doesn't make too much sense, and maybe the description is just throwing me off, but what's the point of the green bridge blocks? And what is considered the same "type" of block? It seems like the objective of the game is to just stack blocks on top of one another, seems pretty uninteresting.

explain: After placing a hexagonal bin near the rug and stacking the chairs on the desks, the player must throw basketball so that they land on top of the hexagonal bin. The player earns 1 point for every chair that is stacked on a desk, and 40 points for every basketball that lands on top of the bin.
overall: So the game is like two different games, each with their own scoring systems. Stacking chairs on tables seems like it would be a waste of time considering you only get 1 point, while it might obstruct the vision or movement of the ball, which gains 40 points when it lands on the bin. Seems like the game should just be throwing a basketball in the bin, no chairs involved.

explain: This game is very simple, throw a dodgeball on top of a hexagonal bin. The player earns 1 point for each dodgeball that successfully lands on top of the bin.
overall: This game seems pretty boring and simple. Just throw a dodgeball on top of the bin. My overall impression here is pretty negative simply because it seems so mundane.

explain: in this game,players set up a scenario where they have a desk and a dodgeball
overall: This game seems like a straightforward and physical activity that emphasizes the skill of throwing a dodgeball accurately. It offers a simple yet engaging way to challenge players' coordination and aiming abilities while providing a clear and measurable scoring system based on the number of successful throws. While it may lack the complexity of some strategy-based games, its simplicity could make it enjoyable for casual play or as a quick and energetic activity. Overall, it seems like a fun way to test and improve throwing skills in a lighthearted setting.

explain: players have two main task,throwing dodgeballs to land them inside and on top of a hexagonal bin
overall: This game seems like an intriguing blend of physical dexterity, spatial reasoning, and strategic thinking. Players must master the skill of throwing dodgeballs accurately while also strategically moving cube blocks to optimize their score. The additional challenge of creating specific arrangements with the blocks adds depth to the gameplay and encourages players to think creatively about their movements. Overall, it appears to offer a dynamic and engaging experience that could appeal to a wide range of players,

explain:
One point shall be awarded if a cube and a rectangle occupy the safe top surface of a cube one level below. 
Checker:
=>(Cube_Top+Rect_Top)/
Cube_Bottom 
==> return +1

One point shall be awarded when two cubes occupy the same top surface of a rectangle which rests on the top surface of a cube, if and only if, the rectangle and bottom cube share the same type classification. 
Checker:
=>(Cube_Top1+Cube_Top2) / 
Rect / 
Cube_Bottom 
==> if type(Rect) === type(Cube_Bottom) 
===> return +1

One point shall be awarded when one rectangle block rests on the top surface of a cube that rests on the topside of another cube, if and only if the two cube blocks share a type classification. 
Checker:
=> Rect / 
Cube_Middle / 
Cube_Bottom 
==> if type(Cube_Middle) === type(Cube_Bottom) 
===> return +1

The final user score will be the value of the total number of instances that each configuration is present at time of completion. There are no restrictions to limit the combining of such rules to indicate that the blocks are point independent and so the user may combine the shape combination requirements to maximize the score. For the purposes of the same, a block type should be considered as the color of the block such that a pair of common colored blocks will count as having the same type.
overall: It seems like the design was intending to accomplish a goal of being overly complicated. I do not want to speculate for the reasons, but I believe it would make for a good mental exercise for flexing the logic muscle. It would be able to occupy my interest, but would not make for a fun time for children. I could see some fun with a multiplayer version with a shared dialogue as a team building exercise. It would help to know whether my assumption about the type matching is correct with my guess that color reflects a block type. Otherwise it would be impossible for a cube and a rectangle to share a type, because a cube cannot be a rectangle.

explain: The user may attempt to move credit cards (CC) and compact discs (CD) into the hexbin while a cube-block is in motion. A cube block is considered in motion so long as the item has  a changing position and that the block has been released into the environment by the user. One point shall be awarded fro each CC or CD inside the hexbin, and one point shall be deducted for each thrown block which has come to rest.
overall: As I understand the instructions, the game has a shortcut available if the user can somehow spin the top section of the office chairs prior to throwing and then toss the cube such that it lands on the flat top side of the now rotating office chair. The task will be quite difficult to start out, but I expect that it is a very steep learning curve and can be picked up without too much practice. From there, it is a simple race against the forces of gravity to relocate all the CC and CD into the hexbin. It is not clear if the transfers must happen one item at a time or if bulk movements are possible.

The player earns 1 point for every chair that is stacked on a desk, and 40 points for every basketball that lands on top of the bin.
overall: So the game is like two different games, each with their own scoring systems. Stacking chairs on tables seems like it would be a waste of time considering you only get 1 point, while it might obstruct the vision or movement of the ball, which gains 40 points when it lands on the bin. Seems like the game should just be throwing a basketball in the bin, no chairs involved.

overall: This game is very confusing to me. I don't completely understand the point of it or how it is supposed to be fun to play or watch. I wouldn't really want to try this one or recommend it.

explain: This game you want to throw dodgeballs so they land inside and on top of the hexagonal bin. You will score 1 point for each dodgeball that stops moving when it is inside and on top of the bin.

explain: In this game you will place the hexagonal bin near the rug and keep it there the whole game. The point is to throw dodgeballs and tan cylindrical blocks at the bin and have the dodgeballs land on top of the bin but the tan cylindrical blocks land inside. You score 1 point for each dodgeball that lands on top of the bin and 6 points for each additional one that lands on top. Then 1 point for each tan cylindrical block that lands inside the bin, with your final score being the sum of all the points earned.
overall: The scoring for this game doesn't make the most sense to me. It also doesn't sound the most enjoyable but I may not understand it fully. I would try it and see if my impression changes but it just seems a bit too complicated to me.
